Opening and closing of the labellar “mandibles” is probably controlled by the same mechanisms as for the labellar lobes themselves. Labellum spreading and closing is known to be controlled by a pair of thin muscles whose origins are at the base of the theca/haustellum and the insertions at the base of the labellum (

). ffle muscle is designated as no. “7” by 

and “z” in 

: fig. 11). Its insertion point is almost certainly the lateral labellar sclerite, possibly also the dorsal sclerite (
fig. 4A
).

Lastly, the “mandibles” could be used in male-male aggression. Male aggression is common in drosophilids, even among species of
Drosophila
(e.g.,
: table 2). In some drosophilid genera the males are territorial and pugnacious, engaging in ritualistic head butting (they don’t make actual contact), which is why there has been repeated origin of hypercephalic (broad-headed) males in the family, in
Zygothrica spp.
